{"add":{"doc":{"id":"4274aa10ba2816fbe44875c186c25e756ed1d915a7069cbc20b25675c640b932","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/21/HMB_Bern_New_Bern_Caleb_Bradham.jpg/220px-HMB_Bern_New_Bern_Caleb_Bradham.jpg","previous":[],"after":["The drink Pepsi was first introduced as \"Brad's Drink\"[2] in New Bern, North Carolina, United States, in 1893 by Caleb Bradham, who made it at his drugstore where the drink was sold. It was renamed Pepsi Cola in 1898, named after the digestive enzyme pepsin and kola nuts used in the recipe. The original recipe also included sugar and vanilla.[3] Bradham sought to create a fountain drink that was appealing and would aid in digestion and boost energy.[2]"]}}}